          "body": "Verse 5 is the psalm's theological fulcrum. At the precise nadir of the lament — after naming total abandonment in verse 4 — David makes the psalm's central declaration: 'You are my refuge, my portion in the land of the living.' The two nouns carry enormous theological freight. *Machaseh* (refuge) is the shelter-word of the Psalter (Psalms 46:1; 62:8; 91:2) — but here it comes after the explicit statement that *no other refuge exists* (v.4, *manos*). The absence of all human refuge has not left David shelterless; it has cleared the field so that God alone is seen as the shelter. *Cheleq* (portion, allotment) is the Levitical inheritance word — the same language used when Moses tells Aaron and the Levites that the LORD is their portion, their inheritance, because they receive no land (Numbers 18:20; cf. Psalm 16:5 and 73:26 where Asaph uses it in nearly identical terms). To call God 'my portion' from inside a cave, with no land, no allies, and no visible inheritance, is to live by the same logic as the Levites — to regard God Himself as the total inheritance when everything else is stripped away."
