          "title": "Petition grounded in weakness — the argument from disproportion",
          "body": "Verses 6-7 are the psalm's petition, and they are structured around two *for* clauses that present David's case before God. 'For I am brought very low' (*dalal me'od* — greatly diminished, brought down) — personal weakness is presented as a reason for divine action, not an embarrassment to conceal. 'For they are too strong for me' (*amats mimmenni* — mightier than I) — the enemy's superior strength is likewise offered as a ground for God to act. This is lament rhetoric at its most precise: David does not minimize his danger or his weakness; he maximizes both in order to maximize God's glory in the deliverance. The petition itself is equally direct: 'Deliver me from my persecutors' (*natsal me min-radaph*) — snatch me out from among those who pursue me. And the *so that* of verse 7 names the goal: 'so that I may give thanks to Your name.' The deliverance is not an end in itself; it is the precondition for praise. The righteous who will surround David after his deliverance (the communal gathering of v.7b) will themselves be witnesses to God's bounty. Individual rescue becomes communal testimony."
