        "excerpt": "When my spirit was overwhelmed within me, You knew my path. In the way where I walk they have hidden a trap for me.",
        "body": "Verses 3-4 are the psalm's diagnostic center — the description of what has happened and what is currently happening to David. Verse 3 contains the psalm's most significant theological juxtaposition: 'When my spirit was overwhelmed within me, You knew my path.' The *when* clause names the inner experience — *ruach ataph*, the spirit fainting, the animating inner life collapsing under weight. The main clause asserts divine knowledge at precisely that moment. God's omniscience does not suspend itself when the believer's spirit fails; it operates continuously, independent of the believer's inner condition.\n\nBut the following clause complicates the comfort: 'in the way where I walk, they have hidden a trap.' God knew the path, and the trap is on the path. This is the psalm refusing easy resolution. The divine knowledge of the path does not mean the path is clear; it means God knows every inch of it, including the ambush point. The *pach* (bird-trap, snare) is a hidden danger — the image of enemies who work by concealment, who set their malice before David walks into it.\n\nVerse 4 extends the crisis into the social dimension and the results are devastating. The three-part inventory — no one who regards me (literally, *no one recognizes me*, *ayin nakhar*), no refuge (*manos* — the word for escape, flight), no one who cares for my soul (*darash nephesh*) — constitutes a complete picture of social abandonment. To the right was the position of an advocate, a legal defender, a military protector. David scans that position and finds *ayin* — nothing, no one. The same word closes the verse: *ayin* again. The repetition frames the entire verse as an inventory of absence.\n\nSpurgeon identifies this verse as 'one of the most plaintive in all the Psalter — not self-pity, but an honest, careful survey of the situation that God Himself is being asked to verify.' The psalm does not ask God to believe something untrue about David's situation; it invites God to look at it as it actually is.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ruach ataph* (spirit overwhelmed/fainted, v.3) appears in Psalms 77:3 and 143:4 — a recognized language of spiritual collapse. *Pach* (snare/trap) is specifically a fowler's trap, implying enemies who lie in wait with patience. *Manos* (escape/refuge, v.4) is the negative counterpart to *machaseh* (refuge) in v.5 — the very word for human refuge that is absent in v.4 becomes the word for divine refuge that is present in v.5."
